metadata.name: Hatch Field 003 #68
metadata.description:
P5js drawing on fx(hash). Experimenting with translating recent work in done in Grasshopper exploring hatch patterns to p5.js. This iteration begins to explore generative landscapes. 
By Andrew Kudless / Matsys @matsysdesign

There are eight feature groups:
- Sky Hue: Red, Orange, Yellow, Spring Green, Green, Ocean Green, Cyan, Sky Blue, Blue, Purple, Magenta, and Crimson. Each has the same random chance of being the sky color (8%).
- Earth Hue: The earth color is related to the sky color. It will never be the same color.
- Sun Color: The sun color is related to the sky color, but shouldn't be the same, but may get close.
- Hue Range: Narrow (14%), Wide (51%), and Infinite(34%)
- Lineweight: Thin (25%), Medium (25%), Thick (25%), Extra Thick (25%)
- Fray: Loose (75%), Tight (25%)
- Horizon: Low (25%), Mid (25%), High (50%)
- Visibility: Clear(50%), Scatter Clouds (30%), Overcast (20%)

metadata.name: Taiga #79
metadata.description:
Generate Tall pines, spruces in atmospheric environment. I need to draw anything I feel around, any story, any relations and any environment. colors are beautiful but can not describe many moments and many atmospheres. this gray scale feeling is about my world. Feeling full of loneliness and sadness, but I know it's generated in my mind. it's not real!

All is generative! Features and variations exist in tree types, atmosphere background-foregrounds, flyings.

=========== Controls ===========
🔸 Press F key to change view.
🔸 Press S key to save high resolution image.

metadata.name: Décollage #253
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: Mosaic #855
metadata.description:
---
Notes:
- Click to pause/unpause
- The aspect ratio is fixed 1:1 because of the way the grid and movements are generated to make sure they're the same on all screens. 
---
Description:
An 80X80 grid of tiles are scrambled, shuffled, shifted, streamed, transported,
conveyed, moved, deposited. 

There are 15 initial tile states and 5 color palettes. A set of 12 unique motion patterns
are generated for each piece. 
---
Acknowledgements:
This piece is inspired by Kim Asendorf, whose pixel-level algorithms I'm
transfixed by, and Ksawery Komputery, whose algorithmic tile-works I'm crazy
about. 
---
Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5.js 
December 2021, Germany
